'''Tsuge no Ōyamanushi''' (闘鶏大山主, birth and death years unknown) was a {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}} {{ill|local chieftain|ja|豪族|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and one of the rulers of the {{ill|Tsuge no Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|闘鶏国造|1=Tsuge no Kuni no Miyatsuko|2=ja|3=闘鶏国造|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. He is also referred to as '''Tsuge Inaki Ōyamanushi no Mikoto''' (闘鶏稲置大山主命) and '''Kuni no Miyatsuko Ōyamanushi no Kimi''' (国造大山主君).

== Overview ==

Tsuge no Ōyamanushi was a figure of the {{ill|Tsuge no Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|闘鶏国造|1=Tsuge no Kuni no Miyatsuko|2=ja|3=闘鶏国造|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, one of the ancient Japanese administrative units. According to the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, he presented ice to the imperial court during the reign of {{ill|Emperor Nintoku|ja|仁徳天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

== The Himuro of Tsuge ==

According to volume 11 of the Nihon Shoki, in the 62nd year of Emperor Nintoku's reign (estimated to be 375 CE), {{ill|Prince Nukata no Ōnakatsuhiko|ja|額田大中彦皇子|qq=draft|qq=draft}} went hunting in {{ill|Tsuge|ja|闘鶏|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (present-day {{ill|Tsuge, Nara City|ja|奈良市都祁村|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}). There, he discovered something resembling a hut in the middle of a field. When he sent someone to investigate, it was identified as a cave (muro). He summoned Tsuge no Ōyamanushi, the local ruler, to inquire about its purpose.

{{quote|
Prince Nukata: "What is that cavity in the middle of the field?"

Ōyamanushi: "It is a {{ill|Himuro|ja|氷室|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (ice chamber)."

Prince Nukata: "How is it stored, and what is it used for?"

Ōyamanushi: "We dig the ground to a depth of over one jō (approximately 3 meters), cover it with grass, and place thick layers of {{ill|chigaya grass|ja|茅|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and reeds. The ice is then placed on top. Even after the summer passes, it does not melt. It is used during the hot months by soaking it in water and sake."
}}

After this exchange, Prince Nukata no Ōnakatsuhiko understood how to store ice and presented it to the emperor. From that time on, the imperial court began storing ice during the month of {{ill|Shiwasu|ja|師走|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (December) and distributing it during {{ill|Kisaragi|ja|如月|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (February).<ref>Nihon Shoki, Emperor Nintoku, 62nd Year of Reign.</ref>

At {{ill|Himuro Shrines|ja|氷室神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} across Japan, including those in {{ill|Nara City|ja|奈良市|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Kyoto City|ja|京都市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Ōyamanushi is enshrined alongside Prince Nukata no Ōnakatsuhiko and Emperor Nintoku. Additionally, it is well-known that {{ill|Prince Nagaya|ja|長屋王|qq=draft|qq=draft}} owned a Himuro and consumed milk, with wooden tablets confirming the use of the Tsuge Himuro.

== Shrines Dedicated to Himuro ==

* {{ill|Himuro Shrine|ja|氷室神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Kasugano, Nara City, Nara Prefecture)

